<DOC><DOCNO> AP880913-0233 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0053EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-13 0491</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0516</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Drought and hot weather nibbled at thenation's corn and soybean crops last month, but new AgricultureDepartment estimates show most of the damage was done in June andJuly.   Officials held Monday to an earlier prediction that consumerfood prices would rise an average of only 3 percent to 5 percentthis year, with about 1 percent of the rise caused by drought. Afurther increase is expected in 1989.   The new projections for the size of crops, based on Sept. 1surveys, were down by less than 1 percent from the forecast a monthago.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than 500 federal savings institutionregulators have been exempted illegally from government salarylimits, according to a congressional report.   The General Accounting Office, in a report Monday, saidemployees of three subsidiaries of the Federal Home Loan Bank Boardare, in fact, federal employees and should be subject to civilservice pay classifications. The top civil service salary is$75,500 a year.   Salaries have ranged as high as $150,000.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal regulators have decided the staffoverseeing the Pilgrim nuclear power plant is ready to handle arestart under intense monitoring, an inspector says.   The Boston Edison Co. plant has been shut down under governmentorder since 1986.   Nuclear Regulatory Commission inspectors recently found no``fundamental flaws'' that would inhibit reactor or public safetyduring plant operation, it was reported Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Apple Computer Inc. announced priceincreases ranging up to 29 percent for some of its personalcomputers, external drives, monitors, printers and expansion kits.   One reason for the increases is that computer memory chips havegone up in price. Because of strong sales, Apple has been forced tobuy some chips at premium prices on the spot market, the companysaid Monday.   The Macintosh II rose 29 percent to $4,869 from $3,769. Theprice of the Macintosh Plus remains unchanged at $1,799.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Winnebagos, those behemoths of America's wide-openspaces, have launched in the home of the compact car with theblessings of the Japanese government.   The venture announced Monday between Mitsubishi Corp. andWinnebago Industries Inc. of Forest City, Iowa, had the glitz ofprofessional marketing.   The Japanese government is seeking to cut Japan's $60 billionannual trade surplus with the United States by encouraging moreimports of American goods into Japan.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market showed little movement in a listless sessionMonday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 3.56points to 2,072.37 while the broad market fell.   Oil futures prices fell below $14 a barrel Monday, but surgedback to finish the day higher after Saudi Arabia's King Fahd calledfor production discipline among OPEC nations.   Bond prices fell in thin trading in reaction to the jump in oilprices. The dollar weakened marginally. Grain and soybean futureswere mixed.</TEXT></DOC>